-- BoE's Carney says solving 'too big to fail' still top priority
-- 
-- Tue May 27, 2014 03:53PM EDT
-- None



LONDON, May 27 (Reuters) - Solving the problem of banks that are 'too big to fail' is still the most pressing regulatory issue for the Bank of England, six years after the start of the financial crisis, Governor Mark Carney said on Tuesday.

"It's at the top of the priority list," he told guests at a a conference on 'inclusive capitalism'.